const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is SLI and why is it so rare now?',
    answer:
      "SLI (Scalable Link Interface) is NVIDIA's old technology for running two or more graphics cards in parallel to share the rendering workload. NVIDIA officially ended consumer SLI support after the RTX 20-series — the RTX 30-series only kept it on the flagship RTX 3090 via NVLink, and the entire RTX 40 and 50-series consumer line has no multi-GPU support at all. Combined with most modern games dropping SLI profiles years ago, multi-GPU rigs are now genuinely uncommon. I rarely see one come through the workshop.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Is SLI worth running today?',
    answer:
      "For gaming, mostly no — modern games either don't support SLI at all or scale poorly with the second card. For the right workloads though, two GPUs still pull their weight: GPU rendering in Blender, V-Ray, Octane, and Redshift use every card you give them. Same with AI/ML workloads (Stable Diffusion batch jobs, local LLMs with large VRAM needs), some CAD/CAM software, and a handful of older games that still scale beautifully (the original Crysis trilogy, older Battlefield titles, classic Witcher 3 SLI profiles).",
  },
  {
    question: "Why does NVIDIA not support SLI on new cards?",
    answer:
      "Three reasons. DirectX 12 shifted multi-GPU responsibility from the driver to the game developer (called \"explicit multi-adapter\"), and almost no developer bothered to implement it. Driver-level SLI was expensive for NVIDIA to maintain and the user base shrank as cards got powerful enough to run anything on a single GPU. And NVIDIA pushed NVLink as a successor for professional workloads only, leaving consumer multi-GPU to die quietly.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I still buy SLI parts in 2026?',
    answer:
      "Yes but you're shopping the used market. SLI bridges, compatible motherboards (need 2+ x8 PCIe slots and SLI certification), and the actual GPU pairs (matched models, ideally same brand/BIOS) all turn up on eBay, Reddit hardware swap, and CEX. Prices on older flagship cards like the GTX 1080 Ti and RTX 2080 Ti have actually held up because of legacy SLI use, GPU rendering, and AI workloads. If you have one of these rigs, look after it — replacements are getting scarcer.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Do you service custom gaming PCs and rare builds in Romford?',
    answer:
      "Yes — custom-build maintenance, AIO water-cooler service, dust-outs, repaste jobs, PSU upgrades, BIOS updates, and Windows reinstalls. I particularly enjoy the older enthusiast builds. If you've got an SLI rig, a custom watercooled loop, or any unusual build that needs work, I'm comfortable with it. Get in touch with photos and I'll quote it.",
  },
  {
    question: 'Would you build a new SLI PC in 2026?',
    answer:
      "For gaming, no — I'd put the money into a single high-end card (RTX 4080/4090, RTX 5080/5090). For specific GPU compute workloads or as a passion build with character, absolutely. A clean RTX 2080 Ti or GTX 1080 Ti SLI build is still a beast and has a personality that no modern single-card build has. If you've got a use case for it and the budget, I'll help you spec one out.",
  },
];
